WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.073
Welcome back! Today we're revising another key topic: the Water Cycle.

2
00:00:06.073 --> 00:00:11.002
We'll cover the three states of water, evaporation and condensation,

3
00:00:11.002 --> 00:00:16.583
how rain is really made, and the exact phrases that score marks in Section B.

4
00:00:17.583 --> 00:00:22.798
Water exists in three states. Solid, as ice, with a fixed shape and volume.

5
00:00:22.798 --> 00:00:26.760
Liquid, as water, with no fixed shape but a fixed volume.

6
00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:30.653
And gas, as water vapour, with no fixed shape or volume.

7
00:00:30.653 --> 00:00:35.242
Water changes from one state to another by gaining or losing heat,

8
00:00:35.242 --> 00:00:40.525
just like we learnt in the Heat topic. Gain heat to melt, evaporate or boil.

9
00:00:40.525 --> 00:00:42.750
Lose heat to freeze or condense.

10
00:00:43.750 --> 00:00:47.941
Here's the biggest trap in this topic: water vapour is invisible!

11
00:00:47.941 --> 00:00:50.649
If you can see it, it is not water vapour.

12
00:00:50.649 --> 00:00:54.776
Steam, mist, fog and clouds are all made of tiny water droplets,

13
00:00:54.776 --> 00:00:57.032
formed when water vapour condenses.

14
00:00:57.032 --> 00:01:01.288
So never write, I can see the water vapour rising from the kettle.

15
00:01:01.288 --> 00:01:04.576
Write: the white steam seen is tiny water droplets,

16
00:01:04.576 --> 00:01:08.509
formed when the hot water vapour condensed in the cooler air.

17
00:01:09.509 --> 00:01:11.224
Concept two: evaporation.

18
00:01:11.224 --> 00:01:16.642
Memorise this sentence: water gains heat from the surroundings, mainly the Sun,

19
00:01:16.642 --> 00:01:19.249
and evaporates to become water vapour.

20
00:01:19.249 --> 00:01:25.148
Evaporation is slow, happens at any temperature, and only at the surface of the water.

21
00:01:25.148 --> 00:01:30.909
And remember, the Sun is the main source of heat that drives the entire water cycle.

22
00:01:31.909 --> 00:01:37.137
Four factors make evaporation faster, and examiners love all of them.

23
00:01:37.137 --> 00:01:41.835
One: higher temperature, so water gains heat at a faster rate.

24
00:01:41.835 --> 00:01:47.670
Two: a larger exposed surface area, so more water is in contact with the air.

25
00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:53.049
Three: moving air, or wind, which carries the water vapour away faster.

26
00:01:53.049 --> 00:01:58.277
And four: drier surrounding air, which can take in more water vapour.

27
00:01:58.277 --> 00:02:04.339
Put them together: wet clothes dry fastest when spread out, on a hot, windy day!

28
00:02:05.339 --> 00:02:07.332
Concept three: condensation.

29
00:02:07.332 --> 00:02:13.595
Memorise this one too: water vapour in the air comes into contact with a cooler surface,

30
00:02:13.595 --> 00:02:17.225
loses heat, and condenses into tiny water droplets.

31
00:02:17.225 --> 00:02:21.140
Condensation happens faster when the surface is cooler.

32
00:02:21.140 --> 00:02:25.339
It's the opposite of evaporation: heat is lost, not gained.

33
00:02:26.339 --> 00:02:29.597
Now let's put it all together: the water cycle.

34
00:02:29.597 --> 00:02:35.074
Water gains heat from the Sun and evaporates. The water vapour rises and cools.

35
00:02:35.074 --> 00:02:36.807
It condenses into clouds.

36
00:02:36.807 --> 00:02:41.868
The droplets combine and fall as rain, which collects in seas and rivers,

37
00:02:41.868 --> 00:02:43.393
and the cycle repeats.

38
00:02:43.393 --> 00:02:49.493
Because water keeps going round and round, Earth has a continuous supply of fresh water.

39
00:02:50.493 --> 00:02:54.145
Let's go stage by stage. Stage one: evaporation.

40
00:02:54.145 --> 00:03:01.068
Water from seas, rivers and lakes gains heat from the Sun and evaporates to become water va

41
00:03:01.068 --> 00:03:01.448
pour.

42
00:03:01.448 --> 00:03:08.219
Stage two: the water vapour rises, and high up in the sky, the surrounding air is cooler.

43
00:03:09.219 --> 00:03:11.177
Stage three: condensation.

44
00:03:11.177 --> 00:03:17.577
The water vapour loses heat to the cooler air and condenses into tiny water droplets.

45
00:03:17.577 --> 00:03:21.868
Millions of these droplets form clouds. Stage four: rain.

46
00:03:21.868 --> 00:03:26.311
The tiny droplets combine to form bigger, heavier droplets.

47
00:03:26.311 --> 00:03:32.711
When they become too heavy to stay up, they fall as rain. And stage five: collection.

48
00:03:32.711 --> 00:03:39.186
Rainwater flows back into drains, rivers, lakes and seas, and the whole cycle repeats.

49
00:03:40.186 --> 00:03:46.390
Trap alert! Clouds do not melt to form rain. Clouds are not solid, so they cannot melt!

50
00:03:46.390 --> 00:03:51.524
Write: the tiny water droplets combine to form bigger, heavier droplets,

51
00:03:51.524 --> 00:03:57.157
which fall as rain. And here's another one: never write, the water disappeared.

52
00:03:57.157 --> 00:03:59.153
Water never just disappears.

53
00:03:59.153 --> 00:04:03.931
Write: the water gained heat and evaporated to become water vapour.

54
00:04:03.931 --> 00:04:06.213
Always say where the water went.

55
00:04:07.213 --> 00:04:12.898
Here's the classic question: why do water droplets form on the outside of a glass of iced w

56
00:04:12.898 --> 00:04:13.210
ater?

57
00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:18.895
The model answer: water vapour in the surrounding air came into contact with the cooler out

58
00:04:18.895 --> 00:04:20.395
er surface of the glass.

59
00:04:20.395 --> 00:04:25.455
The water vapour lost heat to the cold surface and condensed into water droplets.

60
00:04:25.455 --> 00:04:29.516
And remember: the droplets come from the water vapour in the air,

61
00:04:29.516 --> 00:04:31.765
not from the water inside the glass!

62
00:04:32.765 --> 00:04:36.159
Why do wet clothes dry faster when spread out?

63
00:04:36.159 --> 00:04:42.357
Larger exposed surface area, so more water is in contact with the air. On a hot day?

64
00:04:42.357 --> 00:04:48.038
More heat from the Sun, so water gains heat at a faster rate. On a windy day?

65
00:04:48.038 --> 00:04:52.318
Moving air carries the water vapour away at a faster rate.

66
00:04:52.318 --> 00:04:54.900
Whichever factor the question uses,

67
00:04:54.900 --> 00:05:00.065
always end your answer with: so the water evaporates at a faster rate.

68
00:05:01.065 --> 00:05:05.827
A quick bridge back to the Heat topic: boiling versus evaporation.

69
00:05:05.827 --> 00:05:08.497
Boiling is fast; evaporation is slow.

70
00:05:08.497 --> 00:05:14.414
Boiling happens only at the boiling point; evaporation happens at any temperature.

71
00:05:14.414 --> 00:05:19.537
Boiling happens throughout the liquid; evaporation only at the surface.

72
00:05:19.537 --> 00:05:23.650
The water cycle runs on evaporation. The sea never boils!

73
00:05:24.650 --> 00:05:30.028
You can see a mini water cycle inside a sealed container, like a terrarium,

74
00:05:30.028 --> 00:05:34.546
or a plastic bag over a plant. Water gains heat and evaporates.

75
00:05:34.546 --> 00:05:39.925
The vapour touches the cooler lid, loses heat, and condenses into droplets.

76
00:05:39.925 --> 00:05:43.869
The droplets combine, become heavy, and fall back down.

77
00:05:43.869 --> 00:05:49.534
Now the trap: in a sealed container, the total amount of water does not change.

78
00:05:49.534 --> 00:05:52.044
It only changes state and location.

79
00:05:52.044 --> 00:05:58.283
But in an open container, water vapour escapes, so the water level decreases over time.

80
00:05:59.283 --> 00:06:04.953
Answering technique for Section B. Use these keywords: gains heat from the Sun.

81
00:06:04.953 --> 00:06:09.833
Loses heat to the cooler surface. Evaporates to become water vapour.

82
00:06:09.833 --> 00:06:16.078
Condenses into water droplets. Larger exposed surface area. At a faster or slower rate.

83
00:06:16.078 --> 00:06:20.958
And: the droplets combine and become heavier. Then use the formulas.

84
00:06:20.958 --> 00:06:27.489
For evaporation: the water gained heat and evaporated to become water vapour at a faster ra

85
00:06:27.489 --> 00:06:28.494
te, because...

86
00:06:28.494 --> 00:06:34.810
For condensation: the water vapour came into contact with the cooler surface, lost heat,

87
00:06:34.810 --> 00:06:37.250
and condensed into water droplets.

88
00:06:38.250 --> 00:06:39.816
Time to test yourself!

89
00:06:39.816 --> 00:06:43.732
The water level in an open pond decreased on a hot day,

90
00:06:43.732 --> 00:06:49.286
even though no one removed any water. Explain. Pause the video and try. Ready?

91
00:06:49.286 --> 00:06:55.694
Here's the answer: the water in the pond gained heat from the Sun and evaporated to become

92
00:06:55.694 --> 00:07:00.750
water vapour, which escaped into the air. So the water level decreased.

93
00:07:01.750 --> 00:07:02.626
Let's recap.

94
00:07:02.626 --> 00:07:09.124
Water exists as ice, water and water vapour, and changes state by gaining or losing heat.

95
00:07:09.124 --> 00:07:14.089
Water vapour is invisible: steam, mist and clouds are tiny droplets.

96
00:07:14.089 --> 00:07:19.711
Evaporation: water gains heat, mainly from the Sun, and becomes water vapour.

97
00:07:19.711 --> 00:07:25.260
It's faster with more heat, more wind, a larger surface area, and drier air.

98
00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:30.882
Condensation: water vapour loses heat on a cooler surface and forms droplets.

99
00:07:30.882 --> 00:07:36.066
Rain forms when droplets combine and become heavier. Clouds never melt!

100
00:07:36.066 --> 00:07:41.250
And the cycle repeats, giving Earth a continuous supply of fresh water.

101
00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:47.639
You've got this! Remember: gain heat to evaporate, lose heat to condense.

102
00:07:47.639 --> 00:07:54.283
Use the answer formulas and the keywords, and those Section B marks will rain down on you.

103
00:07:54.283 --> 00:07:58.417
Good luck with your revision, and all the best for PSLE!
